{{about|the period from 5000 BC to 3300 BC|the succeeding article|List of Bronze Age states}} {{merge|State (polity)#Copper_Age|date=October 2018}} {{Chalcolithic}} [[File:Los Millares recreacion cuadro.jpg|thumb|Painting of a Copper Age walled settlement, [[Los Millares]], [[Iberia]]]] The [[Chalcolithic]] or Copper Age is the transitional period between the [[Neolithic]] and the [[Bronze Age]].<ref name="OED-Chalcolithic">The New Oxford Dictionary of English (1998) {{ISBN|0-19-861263-X}}, p. 301: "'''Chalcolithic''' /,kælkəl'lɪθɪk/ '''adjective''' ''Archaeology'' of, relating to, or denoting a period in the 4th and 3rd millennium BCE, chiefly in the Near East and SE Europe, during which some weapons and tools were made of copper. This period was still largely Neolithic in character. Also called '''Eneolithic'''... Also called '''Copper Age''' - ''Origin'' early 20th cent.: from Greek ''khalkos'' 'copper' + ''lithos'' 'stone' + '''-ic'''".</ref> It is taken to begin around the mid-[[5th millennium BC]], and ends with the beginning of the Bronze Age proper, in the late 4th to 3rd millennium BC, depending on the region.
The Chalcolithic is part of [[prehistory]], but based on archaeological evidence, the emergence of the first [[state (polity)|state societies]] can be inferred, notably in the [[Fertile Crescent]] ([[Sumer]], [[predynastic Egypt]], [[Minoan chronology|Protominoan Crete]]), with late Neolithic societies of comparable complexity emerging in the [[Indus Valley]] ([[Mehrgarh]]) and in [[Neolithic China|China]].
The development of [[state (polity)|states]]—large-scale, populous, politically centralized, and socially stratified polities/societies governed by powerful rulers—marks one of the major milestones in the evolution of human societies. Archaeologists often distinguish between primary (or pristine) states and secondary states. Primary states evolved independently through largely internal developmental processes rather than through the influence of any other pre-existing state.
The earliest known [[State formation#Early state formation|primary states]] appeared in [[Mesopotamia]] c. 3700 BC,{{cn|date=October 2018}} in [[Ancient Egypt|Egypt]] c. 3300 BC,{{cn|date=October 2018}} in the [[Indus Valley Civilization|Indus Valley]] c. 3300 BC,{{cn|date=October 2018}} and in [[Ancient China|China]] c. 1600 BC.{{cn|date=October 2018}}
==List of known polities== {{see|List of cities of the ancient Near East}} {{see also|List of state leaders in the 4th and 3rd millennia BC}} {{unreferenced-section|date=October 2018}} {| class="wikitable sortable" border="1" |- !City !period |- |[[Assur]] |3500 BC |- |[[Bad-tibira]] |5000 BC to 2300 BC |- |[[Eridu]] |5400 BC onward |- |[[Isin]] |3500 to 2100 BC |- |[[Jericho#History|Jericho]] |Neolithic (first settlement) until Late Bronze Age |- |[[Kish (Sumer)|Kish]] |4000 to 2300 BC |- |[[Lagash]] |4000 to 2250 BC |- |[[Heliopolis (ancient Egypt)|Heliopolis]] ([[Predynastic Egypt#Lower Egypt|Lower Egypt]]) | 3500 BC? |- |[[Mari, Syria|Mari]] |5000 to 1759 BC |- |[[Girsu]] |5000 to 2100 BC |- |[[Nippur]] |5000 to 2450 BC |- |[[Susa]] |4200 to 2330 BC |- |[[Nekhen]] ([[Predynastic Egypt#Upper Egypt|Upper Egypt]]) |3500 BC? |- |[[Ur]] |4000 to 2000 BC |- |[[Uruk]] |4000 to 3100 BC |- |}
