{{about|the picture book|the band of the same name|Dogzilla|the ''[[Angry Birds Toons]]'' episode of the same name|List of Angry Birds Toons episodes#Season 2 (2014–15)}} {{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Dogzilla | image = Dogzilla (picture book).jpg| caption = | author = [[Dav Pilkey]] | illustrator = Dav Pilkey | cover_artist = | country = [[United States]] | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | subject = | genre = [[Children's literature|Children's]] | publisher = [[Harcourt, Inc.]] | pub_date = 1993 | media_type = Print ([[Hardback]] & [[Paperback]]) | pages = 32 | isbn = 0-15-204948-7 |isbn_note= ([[Hardback]]), {{ISBNT|0-15-204949-5}} ([[Paperback]]) }}
'''''Dogzilla''''' is a children's [[picture book]] created by [[Dav Pilkey]] that parodies ''[[Godzilla]]'' with a [[Cardigan Welsh Corgi]]. Harcourt, Inc. published this title in 1993. “The illustrations in this book are manipulated photographic collage, heavily retouched with acrylic paint.”<ref name="Pilkey, Dav 1993">Pilkey, Dav. Dogzilla. 1st. San Diego, CA: Harcourt, Inc., 1993. Print. {{ISBN|0-15-204948-7}}, 0-15-204949-5 (pb).</ref> The photographs of the animals are of Pilkey’s own pets: Flash starring as the Big Cheese, Rabies as Professor Scarlett O’Hairy, Dwayne as the Soldier Guy, and Leia as the Monster. Dogzilla is dedicated to John “The Rapper” Wills and the book has been [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|rated EG]], meaning “Extremely Goofy.” A companion title is Dav Pilkey’s ''[[Kat Kong]]'' which spoofs [[King Kong]].
==Plot summary== “It’s time for Mousopolis’s First Annual Barbecue Cook-Off. But just when the fun is about to begin, the irresistible aroma of barbecue sauce awakens the most frightening creature known to mousekind: the dreaded Dogzilla. As her horrible doggy breath fills the streets, the residents of Mousopolis must run for their lives. Can they get rid of that big stinky dog before it’s too late?” <ref name="Pilkey, Dav 1993"/>
==Inspiration for Dogzilla== "The inspiration for ''Dogzilla'' came one day when I was at a friend's house watching one of my favorite movies, ''[[Godzilla vs. Megalon]]''. My friend's son, Nate, was sitting on the floor building a castle out of [[Lego]]. Everything was fine until Nate let his dog, Leia, into the house. Leia came charging into the room and smashed right through the Lego castle. With the mass of little Lego blocks and action figures scattered around her, Leia looked like a silly monster who had just rampaged a city. 'I should write a book about that,' I said. So I did." — Dav Pilkey<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pilkey.com/bookview.php?id%3D2 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-10-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103143650/http://pilkey.com/bookview.php?id=2 |archivedate=2010-01-03 |df= }}</ref>
==Reception== [[Publishers Weekly]] described 'Dogzilla as "featuring a wacky mix of animal photos, art and a deadpan Sam Spade-style narrative."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-15-204949-2 |website=www.publishersweekly.com |title=Dogzilla|publisher=PWxyz LLC |accessdate=12 July 2015 }}</ref> It appears on reading and study lists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wellsfargocenterarts.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/teacher-from-the-black-lagoon-study-guide.pdf= |website=www.wellsfargocenterarts.org |title=The Teacher from the Black Lagoon & Other Story BooksSchool Show Study Guide |date=19 March 2015 |publisher=Wells Fargo Center for the Arts |accessdate=12 July 2015 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.murrieta.k12.ca.us/Page/4066 |website=www.murrieta.k12.ca.us |title=Theme 3: Incredible Stories |publisher=Lisa J. Mails Elementary School |accessdate=12 July 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mae.osceola.k12.fl.us/winter%20vacation%20education%202011%20(3).pdf |website=www.mae.osceola.k12.fl.us |title=Winter Vacation Education (Parent Newsletter) |page=4 |year=2011 |publisher=The School District of Osceola County, Florida |accessdate=12 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712232524/http://www.mae.osceola.k12.fl.us/winter%20vacation%20education%202011%20%283%29.pdf |archivedate=12 July 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mrsmcgillen.com/page33.htm|website=www.mrsmcgillen.com |title=Unit 4: Lesson 19: How can one event lead to a series of adventures |publisher=Patricia McGillen |accessdate=12 July 2015 }}</ref>
