==''Full–fool'' merger==
The '''''full–fool'' merger''' is a conditioned merger of {{IPA|/ʊ/}} and {{IPA|/uː/}} before {{IPA|/l/}}, making pairs like ''pull''/''pool'' and ''full''/''fool'' homophones. The main concentration of the ''pull–pool'' merger is in [[Western Pennsylvania English]], centered around [[Pittsburgh]]. The merger is less consistently but still noticeably present in some speakers of surrounding [[Midland American English]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ling.upenn.edu/phono_atlas/maps/Map5.html |title=Map 5 |publisher=Ling.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-03-02}}</ref> ''[[The Atlas of North American English]]'' also reports this merger, or near-merger, scattered sporadically throughout [[Western American English]], with particular prevalence in some speakers of urban Utahn, [[Californian English|Californian]], and [[New Mexican English]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Labov|Ash|Boberg|2006|pp=70}}</ref> Accents with [[L-vocalization|''L''-vocalization]], such as [[New Zealand English]], [[Estuary English]] and [[Cockney]], may also have the ''full–fool'' merger in most cases, but when a suffix beginning with a vowel is appended, the distinction returns: Hence 'pull' and 'pool' are {{IPA|[pʊo]}}, but 'pulling' is {{IPA|/ˈpʊlɪŋ/}} whereas 'pooling' remains {{IPA|/ˈpuːlɪŋ/}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phon.ucl.ac.uk/home/estuary/transcree-uni.htm |title=Transcribing Estuary English |publisher=Phon.ucl.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-03-02}}</ref>

The ''fill–feel'' merger and ''full–fool'' merger are ''not'' unified in American English; they are found in different parts of the country, and very few people show either or both mergers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ling.upenn.edu/phono_atlas/maps/Map6.html |title=Map 6 |publisher=Ling.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-03-02}}</ref>

==''Hull–hole'' merger==
The '''''hull–hole'' merger''' is a conditioned merger of {{IPA|/ʌ/}} and {{IPA|/oʊ/}} before {{IPA|/l/}} occurring for some speakers of [[English English]] with [[l-vocalization|''l''-vocalization]]. As a result, "hull" and "hole" are homophones as {{IPA|[hɔʊ]}}. The merger is also mentioned by Labov, Ash, and Boberg (2006: 72) as a merger before {{IPA|/l/}} in [[North American English]] that might require further study.

==''Doll–dole'' merger==
The '''''doll–dole'' merger''' is a conditioned merger, for some Londoners, of {{IPA|/ɒ/}} and {{IPA|/əʊ/}} before word-final {{IPA|/l/}}. As a result, ''doll'' and ''dole'' may become homophones.<ref name="wells_317">Wells: 317</ref> If the {{IPA|/l/}} is morpheme-final, as in ''doll''-''dole'', the underlying vowel is still distinguished in derived forms such as ''dolling''/''doling''.<ref name="wells_317"/>

Where the {{IPA|/l/}} is not word-final, however, the distinction is not recoverable. That may lead to ''sold'' having the same vowel sound as ''solve'' as well as [[hypercorrections]] such as {{IPA|/səʊlv/}} for ''solve'' (RP {{IPA|/sɒlv/}}).<ref name="wells_317"/> There do not appear to be any [[minimal pair]]s in this environment since RP {{IPA|/ɒl/}} and {{IPA|/əʊl/}} are in more-or-less complementary distribution in stressed syllables, with {{IPA|/ɒl/}} before {{IPA|/f/}} and {{IPA|/v/}} (e.g. ''golf'', ''dolphin'', ''solve'', ''revolve'') and {{IPA|/əʊl/}} elsewhere (e.g. ''bolt'', ''polka'', ''gold'', ''soldier'', ''holster'').

==''Fool-fall'' homophony==

For some English speakers in the UK, the vowels of ''goose'' and ''thought'' may be merged before dark syllable-final /l/. <ref>{{cite web|last1=Lindsey|first1=Geoff|title=People fool in love (extended mix)|url=http://englishspeechservices.com/blog/people-fool-in-love-extended/|website=Speech Talk Blog|accessdate=25 March 2018}}</ref> This neutralization has been found to exist for clusters of speakers in the southern UK, especially for speakers from areas of the south coast and the Greater London area.<ref>{{cite web|last1=MacKenzie|first1=Laurel|last2=Bailey|first2=George|last3=Turton|first3=Danielle|title=Who pronounces ‘fool’ and ‘fall’ the same?|url=http://projects.alc.manchester.ac.uk/ukdialectmaps/phonological-variation/fool-fall/|website=Our Dialects: Mapping variation in English in the UK|accessdate=25 March 2018|date=2016}}</ref>

==''Goat'' split==
The '''''goat'' split''' is a process that has affected [[London]] dialects and [[Estuary English]].<ref name="wells_312">Wells, p. 312-313</ref><ref>
{{cite book
|title=Estuary English: Levelling at the Interface of RP and South-Eastern British English
|first=Ulrike
|last=Altendorf
|publisher = Gunter Narr Verlag
|year= 2003
|isbn= 3-8233-6022-1
|location=Tübingen
|page=34
|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eHDbDUs5t48C
}}
</ref> In the first phase of the split, the diphthong of ''goat'' {{IPA|/əʊ/}} developed an [[allophone]] {{IPA|[ɒʊ]}} before "dark" (nonprevocalic) {{IPA|/l/}}. Thus ''goal'' no longer had the same vowel as ''goat'' ({{IPA|[ɡɒʊɫ]}} vs. {{IPA|[ɡəʊʔ]}}).<ref name="wells_312"/> In the second phase, the diphthong {{IPA|[ɒʊ]}} spread to other forms of affected words. For example, the realization of ''rolling'' changed from {{IPA|[ˈɹəʊlɪŋ]}} to {{IPA|[ˈɹɒʊlɪŋ]}} on the model of ''roll'' {{IPA|[ɹɒʊɫ]}}. This led to the creation of a [[minimal pair]] for some speakers: ''wholly'' {{IPA|/ˈhɒʊli/}} vs. ''holy'' {{IPA|/ˈhəʊli/}} and thus to phonemicization of the split.

In broad Cockney, the phonetic difference between the two phonemes may be rather small and they may be distinguished by nothing more than the openness of the first element, so that ''goat'' is pronounced {{IPA|[ɡɐɤʔ]}} whereas ''goal'' is pronounced {{IPA|[ɡaɤ]}}.<ref name="wells_312"/>

==''Vile–vial'' merger==
{{refimprove section|date=April 2018}}
The '''''vile–vial'' merger''' is where the words in the ''vile'' set ending with {{IPA|/-ˈaɪl/}} (''bile'', ''file'', ''guile'', ''I'll'', ''Kyle'', ''Lyle'', ''mile'', ''Nile'', ''pile'', ''rile'', ''smile'', ''stile'', ''style'', ''tile'', ''vile'', ''while'', ''wile'') rhyme with words in the ''vial'' set ending with {{IPA|/-ˈaɪəl/}} (''decrial'', ''denial'', ''dial'', ''espial'', ''Niall'', ''phial'', ''trial'', ''vial'', ''viol'').<ref>According to Dictionary.com,  [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/dial dial], [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/trial trial] and [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/vial vial] all specify variable {{IPA|/-ˈaɪəl/}} or {{IPA|/-ˈaɪl/}} pronunciations, while words like [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/bile bile] and [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/style style] only specify {{IPA|/-ˈaɪl/}} pronunciations.</ref>  This merger involves the dephonemicization of [[schwa]] that occurs after a vowel and before {{IPA|/l/}}, causing the vowel-{{IPA|/l/}} sequence to be pronounced as either one or two syllables.

This merger may also be encountered with other vowel rhymes too, including:
* {{IPA|/-ˈeɪl/}} (''gaol'', ''sale'', ''tail'', etc.) and {{IPA|/-ˈeɪəl/}} (''betrayal'', ''Jael''), usually skewing towards two syllables.
* {{IPA|/-ˈɔɪl/}} (''coil'', ''soil'', etc.) and {{IPA|/-ˈɔɪəl/}} (''loyal'', ''royal''), usually skewing towards two syllables.
* {{IPA|/-ˈiːl/}} (''ceil'', ''feel'', ''steal'', etc.) and {{IPA|/-ˈiːəl/}} (''real''), usually skewing towards two syllables.
* {{IPA|/-ˈɔːl/}} (''all'', ''drawl'', ''haul'', etc.) and {{IPA|/-ˈɔːəl/}} (''withdrawal''), usually skewing towards one syllable.
* {{IPA|/-ˈoʊl/}} (''bowl'', ''coal'', ''hole'', ''roll'', ''soul'', etc.) and {{IPA|/-ˈoʊəl/}} (''Joel'', ''Noel''), usually skewing towards one syllable.
* {{IPA|/-ˈuːl/}} (''cool'', ''ghoul'', ''mewl'', ''rule'', ''you'll'', etc.) and {{IPA|/-ˈuːəl/}} (''cruel'', ''dual'', ''duel'', ''fuel'', ''gruel'', ''jewel''), usually skewing towards one syllable.
* {{IPA|/-ˈaʊl/}} (''owl'', ''scowl'', etc.) and {{IPA|/-ˈaʊəl/}} (''bowel'', ''dowel'', ''Powell'', ''towel'', ''trowel'', ''vowel''), inconsistently skewing towards either one or two syllables.  Some words may wander across this boundary even in some non-merging accents, such as ''owl'' with {{IPA|/-ˈaʊəl/}}, and ''bowel'' with {{IPA|/-ˈaʊl/}}.
* In some [[rhotic and non-rhotic accents|rhotic]] accents, {{IPA|/-ˈɜːrl/}} (''girl'', ''hurl'', ''pearl'', etc.) and {{IPA|/-ˈɜːrəl/}} (''referral''), usually skewing towards two syllables.  This historically happened to the word ''squirrel'', which was previously {{IPA|/ˈskwɪrəl/}} (and still is in certain accents), but it actually became one syllable {{IPA|/ˈskwɜː(r)l/}} in [[General American]] today.  But some accents with one-syllable ''squirrel'' later broke it again into two syllables, but as {{IPA|/ˈskwɜːrəl/}}.
* In some rhotic [[father–bother merger|''father–bother'' merger]] accents, {{IPA|/-ˈɑrl/}} (''Carl'', ''marl'', etc.) and {{IPA|/-ˈɑrəl/}} (''coral'', ''moral''), usually skewing towards two syllables.

For many speakers, the vowels in ''cake'', ''meet'', ''vote'' and ''moot'' can become centering diphthongs before {{IPA|/l/}}, leading to pronunciations like {{IPA|[teəl]}}, {{IPA|[tiəl]}}, {{IPA|[toəl]}} and {{IPA|[tuəl]}} for ''tail'', ''teal'', ''toll'' and ''tool''.

==Other mergers==
Labov, Ash, and Boberg (2006:73) mention four mergers before {{IPA|/l/}} that may be under way in some accents of [[North American English]], and which require more study:<ref>{{cite book | author=[[William Labov|Labov, William]], Sharon Ash, and Charles Boberg | year=2006 | title=The Atlas of North American English | location=Berlin | publisher=Mouton-de Gruyter | isbn=3-11-016746-8}}</ref>
* {{IPA|/ʊl/}} and {{IPA|/oʊl/}} (''bull'' vs ''bowl'')
* {{IPA|/ʌl/}} and {{IPA|/ɔːl/}} (''hull'' vs ''hall'')
* {{IPA|/ʊl/}} and {{IPA|/ʌl/}} (''bull'' vs ''hull'')
* {{IPA|/ʌl/}} and {{IPA|/oʊl/}} (''hull'' vs ''hole'') ([[#Hull–hole merger|''Hull–hole'' merger]])

